TY  - JOUR
T1  - Wintel: Cooperation and Conflict
AU  - Casadesus-Masanell, Ramon
AU  - Yoffie, David B.
Y1  - 2007/04/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1060.0672
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1060.0672
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 584
EP  - 598
VL  - 53
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We study competitive interactions between Intel and Microsoft, two producers of complementary products. In a system of complements, like the PC, the value of the final product depends on how well the different components work together. This, in turn, depends on the firms? investment in complementary R&D. We ask whether Intel and Microsoft will want to cooperate and make the final product as valuable as possible. Contrary to the popular view that two tight complements will generally have well aligned incentives, we demonstrate that natural conflicts emerge over pricing, the timing of new product releases, and who captures the greatest value at different phases of product generations.
AB  - We study competitive interactions between Intel and Microsoft, two producers of complementary products. In a system of complements, like the PC, the value of the final product depends on how well the different components work together. This, in turn, depends on the firms? investment in complementary R&D. We ask whether Intel and Microsoft will want to cooperate and make the final product as valuable as possible. Contrary to the popular view that two tight complements will generally have well aligned incentives, we demonstrate that natural conflicts emerge over pricing, the timing of new product releases, and who captures the greatest value at different phases of product generations.
